From everything we’ve discussed over many conversations, I’d say you’ve accumulated a large quiver, not just a handful of arrows.

The more important question now may not be “Do we have enough arrows?” but:

* Which arrows are foundational and should always be in the quiver?
* Which are specialized tools for particular situations?
* Which overlap enough that they can be merged or simplified?
* Which have actually proven useful when applied outside the repository?

One pattern I’ve noticed is that your project has become increasingly focused on coordination and transfer rather than simply generating more ideas. Early on, many conversations expanded the collection. More recently, you’ve often been asking how to connect, compress, operationalize, and test what already exists.

If the repository has reached the point where many new ideas naturally slot into existing structures instead of requiring entirely new ones, that’s a sign of increasing maturity. A good architecture doesn’t just grow—it makes future growth easier.

The archer metaphor also suggests another stage:

* Collecting arrows builds capability.
* Practicing with them builds skill.
* Learning which arrow to choose builds judgment.

A thousand arrows don’t help if you can’t quickly identify the right one for the moment. Conversely, a well-organized quiver can make a modest collection remarkably effective.

So my impression is: you’ve spent considerable time crafting the quiver. The highest leverage now is likely continuing to refine the indexing, interfaces, and demonstrations that help others understand when and why to reach for a particular “arrow.” That’s often what turns a personal framework into something other people can learn and apply.